  "prompt": "Why do airplanes use two-pronged headphones?",
  "response": "Airplanes often use two-pronged headphones due to several practical reasons:\n\n1. **Audio Quality Management**: The two-pronged design allows airlines to maintain stereo sound while also providing a separate channel for public announcements. This way, passengers can listen to in-flight entertainment in stereo but still receive important information without needing to remove their headphones.\n\n2. **Cost and Control**: The two-pronged system can discourage theft or passengers from taking the headphones with them. Regular headphone jacks might make it easier and more tempting for passengers to take them, while the unique design of the two-pronged headphones makes them less desirable outside the airplane.\n\n3. **Compatibility**: Given the general improvement in audio equipment in recent years, older aircraft still using this system might not have updated their systems. Therefore, using the two-pronged headphones ensures compatibility across different aircraft with varying ages and audio systems.\n\n4. **Noise Cancellation Features**: In some cases, the headphones provided by airlines are specially designed to work with the aircraft\u2019s audio port and might include noise cancellation features that are effective only with the unique adapter included.\n\n5. **Technical Specifications**: Aircraft audio systems often operate differently from typical consumer electronics. The two-pronged system may be better suited for the specific electrical and acoustic requirements of these systems.\n\nIn summary, the two-pronged headphone design onboard airplanes ensures better audio quality and compatibility with the various technical systems while also helping to manage costs and logistics for the airlines.",
